\section{The Unexpected Findings of the Expected Utility Theory}

% basics of EUT
As its core, the expected utility theory considers that the value of an outcome is equal to its payoff times its probability, and that agents choose the option with the highest weighted sum  (\cite[15]{McDermott1998}, \cite[173]{Levy1992a}, \cite[88]{Levy1997}). Importantly, it is commonly assumed that all political agents obey the maxims of invariance, dominance, and transitivity leading to the maximization of utility (\cite[291]{McDermott2004}, \cite[719]{Quattrone1988}).\todo{complete references}


% Formal models in clientelism
Since the expected utility theory (EUT) ``was one of the first theories of decision making under risk'' \parencite[15]{McDermott1998}, EUT has dominated political science for the most part (\cite[289]{McDermott2004}, \cite[87]{Levy1997}), and the vote buying literature has been no exception. Just to name a few examples, \textcite{Nichter2008} used game-theoretical techniques to introduce the concept of ``turnout buying,'' suggesting that parties deliver private benefits even when monitoring is absent. \textcite{Gans-Morse2013} offer a formal model to explain that clientelist parties  offer a mix four clientelist strategies during elections (vote buying, turnout buying, abstention buying, and double persuasion), while \textcite[428]{Rueda2014a} ``present[s] a model of vote buying in which a broker sustains bribed voters' compliance by conditioning future bribes.'' Similarly, \textcite[401]{Gallego2014} ``presents a game-theoretical model of political clientelism in which a candidate disciplines a majority of voters through the promise of a future flow of benefit.'' 

% Formal models in clientelism: example and clarification
We contest this traditional approach focused on absolute gains by shifting the attention to losses and context-dependent decision-making processes. It actually seems rather interesting that most vote-buying theories are framed within the EUT without even declaring it, as it if were the default or go-to framework. It needs to be clarified that the root of the problem is \emph{not} methodological (i.e., the use of game theory), but analytical, that is, the assumed decision-making process under risk embedded in the EUT. For instance, electoral explanations based on the EUT contend that voters see elections as ``investments'' \parencite{Downs:1957vg,Bassi2011}, a notion that also holds for clientelist political parties under risk \parencite{Diaz-Cayeros2008}. 

% dont work empirically
We believe that this shift in focus is a valuable exercise because theories based on the EUT contain descriptions of political behaviors that are ``unrealistic'' \parencite[124]{Aldrich2011}. In effect, a large body of experimental research finds that the behavioral expectations under risk do not comport with the EUT (\cite[25]{Battalio1990}, \cite[1]{Mercer2005}). As a matter of fact, Bernoulli---the forefather of the EUT \parencite{Fishburn:1977tb}---``was the first to see [...] that people would not always bet solely on the basis of the expected value of a game'' \parencite[15-16]{McDermott1998}. From a decision-making standpoint, many find that ``the assumptions underlying the classical theory of risky choice are systematically violated'' \parencite[719]{Quattrone1988} and that both ``variance and semivariance ideas of risk [...] have been shown to be inconsistent with von Neumann axioms'' \parencite[1405]{March1987}. Moreover, from an empirical perspective, there seems to be a strong consensus on the idea that ``expected utility theory [...] continually failed empirically'' \parencite[335]{Vis2011}, while others have explained that ``[e]xperiments [...] have revealed that actual behavior and decisions frequently deviate from the neoclassical predictions'' \parencite[167]{Fatas2007}. In sum, the empirical literature consistently finds that ``people systematically violate the predictions of expected utility theory'' \parencite[173]{Barberis2013}. In fact, \textcite[87]{Levy1997} finds ``ironic'' that just as rational choice has become the most influential paradigm in political science, EUT has come under heavy attacks by experimental \emph{and} empirical evidence.

% clarification 
To be clear, much progress has been made in the understanding of clientelism and vote buying \parencite{Hicken2011}. Yet, there are several inconsistencies that authors tend to ignore or treat as unimportant empirical deviations. In this paper we address two important inconsistencies relevant to the understanding of vote buying. We concentrate on these two aspects because both directly speak to the party's decision-making process under risk.

\paragraph{Clientelist Targeting} The first inconsistency that causes confusion in the literature is targeting: Where do rational clientelist political parties should invest their scarce clientelist resources, core or swing voters?\footnote{We only discuss these two ideal types of voters. There are others that for simplicity we do not discuss. For instance, \textcite[7]{Zarazaga2015a} introduces another category (``conditional supporters'') who ``will vote for the party machine only as long as unexpected events do not persuade them to do otherwise.''} Intuitively, from a portfolio-diversification standpoint, investing in both swing and core voters should be the best response: the more diversified the targeted electorate (i.e., the ``portfolio''), the less risk of losing the election (particularly in contexts of secret voting and monitoring and enforcing problems---\cite{Hicken2020}). In fact, according to the financial market, portfolio choice and investment decision-making literatures in economics, ``[m]ost rational models of portfolio choice suggest that investors hold diversified portfolios to reduce or eliminate non-compensated risk'' \parencite{Goetzmann2008}. In the same vein, \textcite[978]{Goyal2003} ``find a significant positive relation between average stock variance and the return on the market.'' 

% if traditional vote-buying theories conformed with the EUT, yet divided views
That is, if traditional vote-buying theories conformed with the EUT, we should see that both voter types are targeted. Yet, the vote-buying literature seems to be quite divided on an issue that---following the expectations of the EUT---should be clear. In fact, \textcite[14]{Carlin2015} state that ``our knowledge of who parties target remains incomplete.'' On the one hand, \textcite{Cox1986} and \textcite[7]{Zarazaga2015a} explain that since constituencies are well known to clientelist parties, they allocate resources to core voters. On the other hand, \textcite{Lindbeck1987,Dixit1996,Stokes2005} argue that since allocating resources to individuals who \emph{ex-ante} vote for the party is a waste, parties target swing voters.

% adds secondary question about possibility
Why would clientelist parties invest in vote buying on swing \emph{or} core voters, exclusively? Moreover, can parties even \emph{identify} either type of voters? We believe that the clientelism literature expects too much from the party's monitoring capacities. Parties operate in very uncertain environments, particularly due to vote secrecy and social stigma, making both monitoring and enforcing very hard to accomplish \parencite{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012,GonzalezOcantos2014,Gonzalez-Ocantos2015,KiewietDeJonge2015,Corstange2018,Hicken2020,Bahamonde2020a}. Hence assuming that parties can ``clinically'' discern who is a swing or a core voter, exceeds the real capacities of clientelist brokers. Ethnographic evidence for the Latin American cases seems to suggest similar ideas \parencite{Gay:1993aa,Gay1998,Auyero2000,Luna2011,Szwarcberg2013}.\footnote{Even normative scholars explain that parties have a hard time identifying voter's electoral intentions. For instance, \textcite[1147]{Dixit1996} explain that clientelist parties track ``constituents' likes and dislikes, \emph{compulsively} participating in a spectrum of events [such as] baptisms and bar mitzvahs.'' Similarly, \textcite[317]{Stokes2005} argues that parties develop skills that allow them to infer whether clients voted for their party by \emph{looking at them in the eyes} (emphasis is mine).} Thus, it is very reasonable that parties not knowing \emph{exactly} who is who, allocate clientelist resources to both types of voters. 

% there are other contributions too
Moving forward, recent contributions suggest that clientelist parties ``may simultaneously target both swing and core groups of voters'' \parencite[1083]{Albertus2012a}, while in a similar vein \textcite[148]{Diaz-Cayeros2008} explains that long-lasting hegemonic parties (such as the PRI in Mexico) seek ``to prevent core voters from defecting in the future,'' but newly elected incumbents in need of forging a new majority coalition target swing voters. In turn, and also considering the role of political contestation on vote buying, \textcite{Corstange2018} explains that parties ``target clientelistic payoffs to inexpensive voters in their strongholds [i.e., core voters], but that head-to-head competition compels them to bid for more expensive voters [i.e., swing voters].'' However, as we explain below, the latter finding on political contestation also seems to run counter to expectations derived from the EUT.


\paragraph{Political Contestation} Another inconsistency that causes confusion in the clientelism literature is political contestation. Intuitively, the more contested an election, the more risks of losing the election, the more incentives to resort to vote buying to prevent that from happening \parencite{Scott1972,Shefter1977,Diaz-Cayeros2008,Corstange2018}. \todo{cite van de Walle 2007} Yet \textcite[205-206]{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012} report that while in the 2008 Nicaraguan elections the incumbent party enjoyed 40\% of the electoral support, 24\% of registered voters were offered a clientelist gift in an election that ``[was] not heavily contested.'' Why would a party buy such a massive amount of votes in a safe and uncontested election? Answering this question \textcite[570]{Weitz-shapiro} suggests that ``there is no consensus about the relationship between high levels of political competition and the phenomenon of clientelism.'' Exploiting the assumptions of the EUT, some have argued that vote buying should be higher in contexts of \emph{low} political contestation. For instance, \textcite{Medina2002} explain that political parties that hold an electoral monopoly tend to offer clientelist goods to deter the entry of political challengers. Similarly, \textcite{Magaloni:2008bq} explains that hegemonic autocracies such as the PRI in Mexico have survived thank to successful deterrence strategies and clientelism. 

Unfortunately, these explanations seem at odds with normative theories in the risk-management and insurance-buying literatures in economics. If we think of vote buying as an insurance against political losses, then  utility-maximiser parties should ``buy insurance'' only in risky scenarios, that is, in cases when there is a high probability that the expected electoral outcome is a loss. As \textcite[111]{Arrow1996} explains, ``those most at risk will buy more insurance than the others,'' a behavior that he describes as ``adverse selection.'' This is in line with others that find that young individuals do not buy long-term care insurance \parencite{Meier1999}. In other words, if traditional theories of vote buying conformed with the EUT, clientelist political parties should buy votes only in cases of risking the election. Yet, they do when risks are low \parencite{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012}. To put it differently, parties should prefer the certain outcome (winning the election) rather than the gamble (buying votes). As \textcite[1405]{March1987} explain, rational agents in the EUT framework, ``when faced with one alternative having a given outcome with certainty, and a second alternative which is a gamble but has the same expected value as the first, [agents] will choose the certain outcome rather than the gamble.''% \footnote{This implies that decision makers should be compensated for taking risky decisions \parencite[1405]{March1987}. Note that the gamble has the \emph{same} expected value (mean) but differs with the certain outcome in its risk (variance).} 

In sum, the way in which the literature assesses clientelist targeting and political contestation seems to suggest that clientelist political parties waste valuable resources, dramatically departing from the predictions made by the EUT. We interpret this ``misbehavior'' \parencite{Thaler:2015vy} as an analytical problem, particularly, a wrong understanding of how political parties make decisions under risk. To solve this misunderstanding, next section introduces prospect theory \parencite{Kahneman1979} to the study of vote buying. Importantly, this section sheds light on why parties do buy votes from both swing and core voters (as found in \cite{Albertus2012a} and \cite{Diaz-Cayeros2008}), and also why they buy votes in contexts of low risk, that is when the most likely scenario is an electoral victory (as found in \cite{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012}). 


\section{Prospect Theory and its Implications for Clientelism: When Losses Loom Larger than Gains}

% the best theory was developed
Prospect theory ``is a theory of decision making under conditions of risk'' \parencite[15]{McDermott1998}, and was developed by \textcite{Kahneman1979} as a way ``to incorporate the observed violations of expected utility into an alternative theory of risky choice'' \parencite[179]{Levy1992a}, one that is based on empirical data \parencite[290]{McDermott2004}. Since its development, prospect theory has emerged as a ``leading alternative'' \parencite[171]{Levy1992a}, ``best available description'' \parencite[173]{Barberis2013} and ``empirically correct theory'' \parencite[334]{Vis2011} about how people evaluate risk \parencite[5]{Ackert2006}, particularly ``[excelling] in providing a model that offers descriptively accurate formulations of the human decision-making process'' \parencite[292]{McDermott2004}.


% influence of the theory--where else this theory has been applied.
The theory has been most influential among IR scholars but just ``limited'' influence in political science in general \parencite[2]{Mercer2005}. Still, in comparative politics, there are several contributions that take prospect theory as a framework. For instance, \textcite{Weyland2002} studies levels of loss aversion of dictatorships when they perform radical economic reforms. \textcite{Vis2009,Vis:2010tq} studies welfare state reform showing that political gains are the necessary condition for not-unpopular reform, while for unpopular reform are deteriorating socio-economic situation, or political losses. In turn, \textcite{Steinacker2006} studies issue salience, \textcite{Schumacher2015} studies party platform change. 


% main principles and contrasts with EUT
Since others have already provided very good reviews of prospect theory \parencite{Levy1992a,Levy1992,Levy1997,McDermott1998,McDermott2004,Mercer2005,Mercer2005,Vis2011,Barberis2013,Linde2017,Vieider2019}, we will limit this section to describe its main components. The theory is based on two mainly empirically-derived concepts \parencite[334]{Vieider2019}. First, utilities are defined over changes in outcomes respect to a reference point (``reference dependence''). Note the sharp contrast with EUT where the focus is on absolute levels of wealth \parencite[5-6]{Ackert2006}. Second, individuals distort probabilities in an asymmetrical non-linear S-shaped way when making risky decisions (``likelihood dependence''). Note also another important difference with EUT where agents are assumed to treat probabilities linearly, ``even with training and effort'' \parencite[293]{McDermott2004}. As \textcite[18]{McDermott1998} clearly puts it, ``prospect theory predicts that individuals tend to be risk averse in a domain of gains [i.e., when things are going well], and relatively risk seeking in a domain of losses [i.e., in the midst of a crisis].'' This distinction also separates prospect theory from EUT where the latter assumes that ``whether we are in a domain of gain or loss should not affect our attitude toward risk'' \parencite[1]{Mercer2005}.


% central idea in prospect theory (Reference dependence)
Reference dependence is the central idea in prospect theory (\cite[178]{Barberis2013}, \cite[40]{McDermott1998}). And such, prospect theory pays special attention to the context in which decision-making processes take place \parencite[293]{McDermott2004}. In simple, prospect theory ``allows people's preferences to depend on the circumstances they face'' (\cite[168]{Fatas2007}, \cite[1412]{March1987}, \cite[294]{McDermott2004}), which is usually \parencite[335]{Vis2011} but not always \parencite[174]{Levy1992a} the \emph{status quo},\footnote{The location of the reference point emerges as a critical factor in the analysis of decisions \parencite[288]{Kahneman1979}. \textcite[174]{Levy1992a} explains that the reference point could also be an ``aspiration level.'' In a similar way, \textcite[1135]{Koszegi2006} develop the idea of a reference point which consists of ``expectations rather than the status quo.'' I owe this point to Salomo Hirvonen.} and how it shifts over time (\cite[28]{McDermott1998}, \cite[301]{McDermott2004}).\footnote{While we do not focus on the role of emotions, others have found that ``sad people will take more risk when trying to avoid a certain loss'' \parencite[6]{Campos-Vazquez2014}.} As \textcite[273]{Kahneman1979} put it more clearly, ``the carriers of value or utility are changes of wealth, rather than final asset positions.'' In fact, contrary to the assumption of invariance \parencite[186]{Barberis2013}, a shift in the reference point should also lead to reversals of preferences \parencite[719]{Quattrone1988}. For instance, there is strong support for the idea that prior losses (or ``sunk costs'') influence decisions, contrary to what normative theorists propose \parencite[643]{Thaler1990}.

% central idea in prospect theory (likelihood dependence)
Likelihood dependence is another central idea in prospect theory. Prospect theory pays considerable attention to losses. \textcite[171]{Levy1992a} explains that individuals ``give more weight to losses than to comparable gains,'' which translates into the famous statement ``losses loom larger than gains.'' Losses have also been the focus in other areas of political science \parencite[298]{McDermott2004}. For instance, \textcite[132]{Lau1985} explains that ``negative information is more influential than comparable positive information.'' 

% likelihood dependence explained
Importantly, the likelihood of the value curve is non-linear. From an analytical point of view, we consider this is \emph{the} feature that out trumps the normative expectations contained in EUT. Formally, the asymmetrical curvature of the likelihood explains why individuals have risk-averse behaviors in choices among gains but risk-acceptant behaviors in choices among losses \parencite[87]{Levy1997}. In the domain of gains, the concavity of the value function encourages risk aversion by undervaluing the probability of success of a gamble relative to a certain outcome (underweighting). However, in the domain of losses, the convexity of the value function encourages risk-seeking behaviors by exaggerating the probabilities of rare but catastrophic losses (overweighting) \parencite[183-184]{Levy1992a}. Typical examples are individuals who tend to underweight likely events such as heart attacks (not changing diet) but tend to overweight rare events such as a plane crash (praying before landing). Unlike theories based on EUT, \textcite{Kahneman:2012tc} explains that ``Underweighting of moderate and high probabilities relative to sure things contributes to risk aversion [while] very low probabilities are either overweighted quite grossly or neglected altogether'' (see also \cite[32]{McDermott1998})\todo{add pages}. % \textcite[32]{McDermott1998} explains that ``prospect theory accounts for these discrepancies by noting the extreme (over)weight and attention that individuals give to small probabilities.'' 

% to conclude PT section: most important empirical finding in PT
In prospect theory, both reference and likelihood dependence lead to a more accurate description of decision-making under risk. In fact, experimental evidence consistently finds evidence about decision-makers distorting probabilities in a non-linear way \parencite[87]{Levy1997}. In particular, the evidence suggests that in the domain of losses, risk-seeking decision-makers take \emph{disproportionate risks} to avoid certain losses, while in the domain of gains, risk-averted decision-makers are \emph{excessively eager} to secure gains \parencite[297, 299-300]{Levy1992}. This is explained because decision-makers ``have difficulty with probability at extreme ranges'' \parencite[30]{McDermott1998}. Finally, it is important to note while attitudes toward risk are usually portrait as aspects of personality \parencite[1406]{March1987}, prospect theory is \emph{not} a personality theory, that is, it is not necessary to know about the individual personality traits of decision-makers in order to predict behavior (\cite[293]{McDermott2004}, \cite[335]{Vis2011})
 
% implications for vote buying
The implications for vote buying are considerable. In sharp contrast to traditional vote-buying theories based on EUT, prospect theory predicts that clientelist parties should buy votes when are probable winners or have experienced important losses in the past, irregardless of whether the voter is a core or a swing voter. 

% 1 why Clientelist parties should buy votes when they are probable winners
Clientelist parties should buy more votes when they are probable winners because decision-makers will exaggerate the small probability of losing the election. We expect vote buying to be higher in favorable electoral scenarios by making vote-buying an attractive strategy due to the absolute aversion and intolerance to the (small) probability of losing the election. The mechanics of such decision-making process should then make clear that there is no ``wasting'' when buying votes in the domain of gains. This is consistent with prospect theory. Empirical studies confirm that ``actors perceive themselves to be in the domain of losses more often than we would normally expect'' (\cite[291]{Levy1992}; see also \parencite{Lau1985}), even if they are not. This implies that loss aversion explains why decision-makers are more concerned to prevent a decline than to increase it \parencite[285]{Levy1992} (see also \cite[89]{Levy1997}). To sum, when things are going well electorally, clientelist political parties will tend to buy more votes because ``future losses hurt more than future gains gratify'' \parencite[285]{Levy1992}.


% 2 why Clientelist parties should buy votes when they have experienced important losses in the past
Clientelist parties should buy more votes when they have experienced important losses in the past, making vote buying an attractive strategy by altering the decision-makers' reference point. Altering the reference point downwards increases (1) risk-seeking behaviors and (2) the tendency of decision-makers to bet on long shots \parencite[286-287]{Kahneman1979}, that is, the tendency of clientelist political parties of incurring in more risks (i.e., vote buying) when things are not going well, and the tendency to aspire winning hard elections even when having a history of past electoral losses. This behavior has been confirmed by others, that is, the tendency of  individuals in the domain of losses to ``break-even'' \parencite{Thaler1990}. This implies that political losers should buy more votes not necessarily because they want to win the next election but because they will try to compensate for past losses. \parencite[297]{Levy1992} notes that the elasticity of the risk-seeking behavior should be quite high because ``the magnitudes of the losses need not be that large in order to induce risk-seeking behavior, even small losses should induce the risk-seeking behavior.'' Consequently, we expect a steeper predicted effect in the data analyses. To sum, ``losses are harder for individuals to accept [hence, when] things are bad or likely to get worse, [decision-makers] are more likely to make risky choices to recover their losses'' \parencite[294]{McDermott2004}. 

   
% Importantly, it should not matter whether the voter is a swing or a core voter. 
% Importantly, it should not matter whether the voter is a swing or a core voter. Besides risking electoral support from the wealthy \parencite{Weitz-shapiro} or from society in general \parencite{GonzalezOcantos2014}, when clientelist political parties are probable winners, they incur in the additional risk of buying votes from unlikely voters, irregardless of where that voter is in the swing-core continuum. Given the impossibility of accurate monitoring \parencite{Nichter2008,Hicken2020}, in risky contexts parties avoid the (small) probability of losing the election by diversifying their electoral portfolio. 










