\end{figure}


% endowments
Both parties received as well different ``endowments'' at random. The idea was to reflect the fact that some parties are wealthier than others, a factor that might increase the probability of vote buying \parencite{Juan-Pablo-Luna:2014wp}. Note that both parties receive the same endowment. Since our experimental design is an in between-subjects design, we should be able to observe and exploit the statistical differences (if any) across ``parties'' with different endowments. Participants acting the ``party'' role accumulated/lost wealth depending on whether they got elected/not-elected. For every time they bought votes at some amount, that amount was discounted from their wealth. For simplicity, voters received zero endowments.\footnote{This is consistent with the vote-buying literature in that both poor and rich voters are prone to receive clientelist offerings \parencite{Bahamonde2018}.} In turn, participants acting the ``voter'' role accumulated/lost wealth depending on whether their party got elected/not-elected (as per traditional EUT voting theories) and on whether they decided to sell/not-sell their vote. It is important to note that following our formal model and \textcite[371]{Tyszler2016}, both ideology and party endowments were common knowledge. 



