\section{Statistical Analyses: What levels of electoral risk drive vote buying?}




% questions
In this section we will analyze two main dependent variables. First, the amount of the vote-buying offer made by parties (if any), and second, whether both parties make clientelist offerings (1, 0 otherwise). Both distributions are plotted in \autoref{dep:var:plot:fig} (left and right panel, respectively). From a statistical point of view, we concentrate on these variables because they show different levels of vote buying in both a continuous and dichotomous fashion. 

% theoretical expectations
From an internal validity standpoint, we expect both measurements to vary with the levels of risk the party is dealing with. Accordingly, if the predictions of our formal model (and the ones of the traditional vote-buying theories based on the EUT) are correct, the amount of the vote-buying offer made by parties should be higher in riskier scenarios (i.e., when facing probable electoral losses). However, we have hypothesized that parties should buy votes due to risk-seeking in the domain of losses (i.e., when experienced prior losses), and due to risk-aversion in the domain of gains (i.e., when being a likely winner hate the idea of loss). Similarly, situations in which both parties simultaneously make clientelist offerings directly resemble highly contested electoral markets. Since the vote share, ideological positions and endowments are public information (as formalized in our game), this is an important advantage of our game. 

From an external validity standpoint, we believe that voters in real elections can estimate with some degree of success actual vote shares\todo{reference}, for instance, by looking at electoral polls. Voters can also identify ideological positions \todo{cite CPS Luna and Zech.} and endowments. For instance, others have studied how voters can identify whether parties are linked to the businesses sector or the blue-collar, grassroots and working-class sectors. 

We should expect such markets to be riskier for parties, hence (according to the game-theoretical model), with more levels of vote buying. We believe this identification strategy appropriately captures the decision-making process under risk of political parties. 

